Oh My Goodness, Oh My Damn is a viral video remix of a Daym Drops YouTube food review that was popularized via lip dubs on TikTok. The chorus of the song, âOh my goodness, oh my damn, oh my goodness, theyâre going ham,â migrated to TikTok on its 10th anniversary in 2022 and became a sound TikTokers use to express their surprise and enjoyment of someone or something âgoing ham.â

On April 26th, 2012, the YouTube food review channel Daym Drops posted a video titled, âFive Guys Burgers and Fries Review.â The post gathered over 11 million views and 200,000 likes in roughly 10 years. On August 15th, the YouTube channel Schmoyoho then uploaded a video remixing the clip into a song, titled âOH MY DAYUM ft. @Daym Drops,â gathering over 44 million views and 600,000 likes in roughly 10 years. SPREAD
On January 30th, 2020, TikToker @haileythebaby posted a video using a snippet from the song and gathered over 900,000 views and over 64,000 likes in nearly two and a half years. On August 24th, 2022, TikToker @nillsis reuploaded the 2012 Schmoyoho remix alongside a text overlay that read, âThis Masterpiece Just Turned 10 Years Old.â The post gathered over 3.3 million plays and over 300,000 likes in nearly three weeks, spreading on the platform over the following month as other TikTokers began using it in lip-dub skits.

All hail the great Cosimo Matassa, the genius who recorded 98% of the music of New Orleans from the late 1940s through the late 1960s.  This guy made your favorite records by Fats Domino, Little Richard, Smiley Lewis, Lee Dorsey, Dr. John, Aaron Neville, Art Neville, Allen Toussaint, Irma Thomas, Shirley and Lee, Frankie Ford, and about a thousand others.  The sound he got was THE coolest sound, like a party was going off in your living room, and he did it without a great deal of equipment.  This mid-1950s shot shows him with a tiny 4-channel Dukane mixer, a Cinema EQ unit, and not much else.  No air conditioning back then, so you know it was a thousand degrees in there, hence the t-shirt.

In later years, Cosimo managed the family grocery in the French Quarter.  One morning around 1999 or 2000, I walked over there after a gig in New Orleans the night before and asked if I could meet Cosimo.  A few minutes later, he came out of the back, a stout little Yoda of a man, and dutifully answered my questions for 15 minutes.

He wanted no credit for his role in creating some of Americaâs most iconic Rhythm and Blues, Rock ânâ Roll, Soul and Funk.

âIt was all about THOSE musicians.  Anybody could have put a few microphones in front of those guys and it would have sounded good.â Despite his protestations to the contrary, no one has ever made records like THAT ever again.  He captured lightning in a bottle.

A belated happy 100th birthday to the Vista Theatre, which first opened as Bard's Hollywood Theatre on October 9th, 1923.

Intended as both a cinema and a vaudeville theatre, the Hollywood Bard was built by downtown theatre proprietor Lou Bard who'd had great success with his College and Hill Street theatres and was looking to expand. Setting his sights on Hollywood, Bard bought up a plot of land at Hollywood & Sunset that had once been part of the backlot for director D. W. Griffith's Reliance-Majestic Film Studios - in fact, it now stands approximately where the towering set of Babylon had been built for the 1916 film "Intolerance" (the studio itself was located where the Vons now stands across the street). Bard then brought in architect Lewis A. Smith, who designed it with a Spanish Colonial Revival exterior, and an Egyptian Revival interior, inspired both by the success of Grauman's Egyptian Theatre and the world's fascination with the discovery of King Tutankhamen's tomb in 1922.

When the theatre opened, 100 years ago yesterday, the opening night program consisted of the premiere of the Baby Peggy comedy short "Tips," filmed nearby at the then-new Ambassador Hotel, followed by a sneak peek of the Universal comedy-drama "The Wild Party," starring Gladys Walton. Vaudeville performances and other shorts also peppered the evening, which was reported as "a fine entertainment for all, and altogether too much for one evening." This first photo was taken that night.

The theatre became the Vista in 1933 and operated through the 1950s, then it became an arthouse theatre in 1960, and then as a porno theatre in 1961. In 1980, the Vista re-opened as a mainstream cinema, but closed in 2020 due to COVID. 

It was purchased by Quentin Tarantino in June of 2021, and is undergoing renovations, hopefully to re-open soon.

Originally built in 1902 as an Arts and Crafts chalet-style home on the remote dunes of what was then known as the city's outside lands, the expanded home sits on the edge of the Presidio.

Adams, a renowned photographer and environmentalist, redesigned the space with his wife in 1929, adding a "grand salon annex" to the original home structure, Sotheby's International Realty said in a press release.

"The merged home became the residential seat of America's most lauded landscape photographer until 1957, when he moved his family to the Monterey Peninsula," the property listing states.

Sotheby's representatives say that Adams' home was a core meeting place for San Francisco's arts community, where guests would frequently bring music and operatic songs to the home's residential salon.
Other perks in the Presidio home include an attic-turned-artist's loft, views of the Golden Gate Bridge and a terraced garden design.

The estate is listed by Sotheby's for $5.45 million and sits along West Clay Park. It features three bedrooms and two baths. Joseph Lucier and Stacey Caen represent the house for Sotheby's.

Aerials of Los Angeles from 1923, as photographed by Captain A.W. Stevens for the US Navy. Seeing all of these together, knowing that they were likely taken within days or hours of each other, is as close of an experience as I have ever had to traveling through time. 

Photos: 

â¢ 1. Bernheimer Estate & Gardens, now Yamashiro. The Lane Mansion (Magic Castle) is visible at bottom.

â¢ 2. The Goodyear Rubber Company, at 6701 S. Central Ave. Looking southwest here, so that's Gage below the plant, w/ McKinley, Stanford, and Avalon to the right. 

â¢ 3. Westlake Park, now Macarthur, with 6th St. to the left and 7th to the right. The bridge extending Wilshire over the lake was added in 1934.

â¢ 4. Pickford-Fairbanks Studios, on Santa Monica Blvd. at Formosa, with film sets for "The Thief of Baghdad.â Today, this is âThe Lot.â

â¢ 5. Salt Lake Oil Field, long before The Grove, Park La Brea, the Original Farmers Market, & Television City were built on top. Corner of Wilshire & Fairfax at bottom left, and you can just make out 3rd street cutting through oilfield. Derricks stretching past La Brea & Highland, all the way to Vine.

â¢ 6. Now Paramount, this was FBO Studios before they became RKO. Gower runs across the bottom, intersecting a tree-lined Melrose on the right. Hollywood Forever Cemetery on the left.

â¢ 7. The Southern Pacific Rail Depot, between Central & Alameda, stretching from 4th to 6th. Everything below is Skid Row, while everything above is now the Arts District. Depot is gone, but lots still standing here, incl. the LA Cold Storage Building, center left.

â¢ 8. Main channel of the Los Angeles Harbor, as fog obscures a densely-populated San Pedro to the right. Center left, you can make out the Japanese fishing village on Terminal Island that was razed during internment. 

â¢ 9. Colorado Street Bridge in Pasadena, with the horseshoe-shaped Rose Bowl Stadium at the top (south end was added in 1928). Vista del Arroyo Hotel at lower right when it was two-story bungalows. Bell-tower not added until 1930.

â¢ 10. The newly-completed Memorial Coliseum, still decorated for the Motion Picture Exposition from Wednesdayâs post.

A woman knocks a black bear off a block wall to save her pets. 

Friends, I really struggled to justify posting this. I do not think promoting this behavior is a good idea because I can totally see it getting someone (or more likely a lot of bears) killed one day. 

I ultimately decided to use the virality of this video in an attempt to innoculate against future occurrences, in the hope that if presented with a choice like this, you'll choose the path that doesn't involve putting your body within striking distance of a momma bear with vulnerable cubs. Ever. 

So first off, let me go ahead and state unequivocally that you should never ever ever approach any wild animal, especially those with offspring, unless all other options have been exhausted.

On the flip side, I also understand the impulse to save your pets. In this case, it worked out the best way possible (for the human at least) but she was soo damn lucky to get out of there in one piece. 

Protective instincts are on full display in this one, and I truly believe that the bear's fixation on the dogs allowed the woman to get close enough to tip the scales in her favor long enough to get the dogs and herself out of harms way.

Just keep in mind that this could have ended very differently, so please don't try this.
